To each observation is associated one of two possible outcome: “B”, benign, or “M”, malign.

levels(brca$y)
## [1] "B" "M"

Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

Data is centered at 0 and scaled to have unitary standard deviation.

x_centered <- sweep(brca$x, 2, colMeans(brca$x))# Subtract the column means

x_scaled <- sweep(x_centered, 2, colSds(brca$x), FUN = "/")# Divide by the column standard deviations

pca <- prcomp(x_scaled)# Perform principal component analysis
summary(pca)

Let’s take a closer look at PC1 and PC2.

data.frame(pca$x[,1:2], type = brca$y) %>%
  ggplot(aes(PC1, PC2, color = type)) +
  geom_point()

Malignant tumors tend to have larger values of PC1 than benign tumors. PC1 actually splits the data so that there is no overlap in the interquartile ranges for benign and malignant samples:

What percentage of each principal component is each variable responsible for?

loadings <- pca$rotation 
percentages <- sweep(x = abs(loadings), MARGIN = 2, 
                      STATS = colSums(abs(loadings)), FUN = "/")*100

When looking at the above heatmap, we must remember that the first components are the most relevant. So, those variables that explain a good part of PC1, for example, are going to be the most relevant overall. We can actually compute the weighted average of the percentages for each variable across the 30 PCs using the variance explained by each PC as weights, so as to better understand the contribution of each variable to the overall variability in the data.

Cumulative proportion of variance reaches 0.95 with PC10.

In training the following algorithms, the first 10 PCs will be used.

Algorithms

Data is split into training and test set using a 80-20 partition.

test_index <- createDataPartition(brca$y, times = 1, p = 0.2, list = FALSE)
test_x <- x_scaled[test_index,]
test_y <- brca$y[test_index]
train_x <- x_scaled[-test_index,]
train_y <- brca$y[-test_index]

The original feature spaces train_x and test_x have been transformed into a new set of features using PCA.

pca10 <- pca
pca10$x <- pca10$x[,1:10]
pca10$rotation<- pca10$rotation[,1:10]

testPC_x <- predict(pca10,test_x)
trainPC_x <- predict(pca10,train_x)

1. Logistic regression model

train_glm <- train(trainPC_x, train_y, method = "glm")
train_glm$finalModel

Performance evaluation on the test set

glm_preds <- predict(train_glm, testPC_x)
matrix_glm <- confusionMatrix(glm_preds,test_y)
df_glm <- data.frame(Accuracy=matrix_glm$overall[1],    
           Sensitivity=matrix_glm$byClass[1],
           Specificity=matrix_glm$byClass[2],
           Prevalence=matrix_glm$byClass[8],
           F1 = matrix_glm$byClass[7],row.names = "GLM")

Final considerations

The following table summarizes Accuracy, Sensitivity, Specificity and F1 for the four models.

##        Accuracy Sensitivity Specificity        F1
## GLM   0.9652174   0.9861111   0.9302326 0.9726027
## Loess 0.9565217   0.9722222   0.9302326 0.9655172
## KNN   0.9739130   0.9861111   0.9534884 0.9793103
## rf    0.9565217   0.9722222   0.9302326 0.9655172

The results obtained from the application of GLM, Loess, KNN and Random Forest algorithms on the test set show good accuracy and F1 scores. The GLM and KNN algorithms stand out with an accuracy of approximately 96-97% and a high F1 score of around 97%. This indicates that these algorithms are effectively making correct predictions and achieving a balance between precision and recall. On the other hand, the Loess algorithm showed a lower accuracy of 91% and a F1 score of 92.75%, which implies that its predictions may not be as accurate as the other algorithms. The Random Forest algorithm demonstrated an accuracy of 95.65% and a F1 score of 96.55%. Although these values are still good, they are not as high as those achieved by the GLM and KNN algorithms.

With respect to sensitivity and specificity, both the GLM and KNN algorithms have high sensitivity and specificity, meaning that they accurately predict both positive and negative cases. The Loess algorithm has a lower sensitivity of 88.89% but a higher specificity of 95.35%. This suggests that it makes fewer false positive predictions, but may also miss some positive cases. The Random Forest algorithm shows a high sensitivity of 97.22% and a good specificity of 93.02%, indicating that it makes accurate predictions in most cases.
